{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471322"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:46:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:46:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"293"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/293"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.58,0.05,0.03,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92270"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/293"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"293"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75569"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"313"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2128"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35939"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92270"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 4-year-old unimmunised boy is brought into a family clinic by his parent. The child has had a night-time cough for the last week that comes in \u0022spasms\u0022, but during the daytime he is well. Several times, he has vomited following a coughing spasm. On examination, he has a normal respiratory rate with an SpO2 of 99% on room air. He is afebrile. Respiratory examination is unremarkable, his tonsils are not inflamed, and otoscopy is normal. Nasopharyngeal aspirate PCR test comes back positive for \u003Cem\u003EBordetella pertussis.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management approach?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit to hospital for observation and amoxycillin","Five day course of oral azithromycin","One week course of trimethoprim-sulphamethoxazole","Vaccinate with DTPa","Supportive management and isolation at home for 14 days"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of coughing spasms (\u0027paroxysms\u0027) with vomiting afterwards raises the suspicion of \u003Cstrong\u003Epertussis (whooping cough).\u003C/strong\u003E Pertussis is a respiratory infection caused by \u003Cem\u003EBordetella pertussis.\u003C/em\u003E Laboratory confirmation is not necessary for diagnosis, but is helpful for infection control as it is a notifiable condition. Laboratory analysis can take several days to confirm the diagnosis and should not delay the start of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with pertussis are infectious 21 days before and after they are symptomatic. They should be excluded from school until completing 5 days of treatment or coughing less than 21 days to prevent transmission to unvaccinated individuals or infants.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnimmunised or partially immunised children diagnosed with pertussis should complete the \u003Cstrong\u003Epertussis immunisation\u003C/strong\u003E schedule following treatment. Prophylactic antibiotics should also be considered for household members or close contacts to prevent transmission to infants less than 6 months of age. In this case, treating this patient with antibiotics is a priority prior to administering pertussis immunisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst-line treatment of pertussis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Efive day course of azithromycin \u003C/strong\u003Ewithin the first 14 days\u003Cstrong\u003E,\u003C/strong\u003E with clarithromycin liquid an option for children unable to swallow tablets. Trimethoprim-sulphamethoxazole can also be given if macrolides are contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECriteria for hospital admission\u003C/strong\u003E include respiratory distress (tachypnoea, retractions, nasal flaring, grunting, and use of accessory muscles), evidence of pneumonia, inability to feed, cyanosis or apnoea, seizures, and infants less than six months of age. As the patient is stable, it is reasonable for him to be managed at home with a course of azithromycin. Amoxicillin is not a recommended antibiotic therapy for whooping cough.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating a one week course of trimethoprim-sulphamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct management option. Trimethoprim-sulphamethoxazole is only given to patients with contraindications to macrolides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive treatment with antibiotics is recommended in patients with early stages of pertussis (catarrhal or paroxysmal stage) to reduce disease severity, reduce spread and prevent complications; therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Esupportive management and isolation at home for 14 days\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diagnosis of pertussis should be done clinically but laboratory confirmation is helpful for public health control.","First-line treatment for pertussis is azithromycin. Clarithromycin liquid can be given to children who are unable to tolerate tablets."],"references":["Nguyen VTN, Simon L. Pertussis: The Whooping Cough. Prim Care Clin Office Pract 2018; 45:423-31.","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Whooping Cough (Pertussis). Clinical Practice Guidelines 2022. Viewed October 2022. Accessible via: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Whooping_Cough_Pertussis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75569"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"293"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75569"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T22:51:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T08:56:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"293"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92270"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"cr